The start symbol S can select the rule S → NT14 NT15.  
To obtain the first terminal t4 we let  

 NT14 ⇒ NT20 NT19 with NT20 → 't4'.  

This accounts for the first word.  
From this point NT19, NT15 and the richly-recursive non-terminals they expand to (NT6, NT17, NT11, NT0, NT7 …) contain mutually-recursive rules of the form X → YZ together with many unit productions for every terminal that appears in the string.  
Because of productions such as

 NT6 → NT16 NT13, NT16 → NT2 NT11, NT2 → NT1 NT14, NT14 → NT20 NT19, …  
 NT11 → NT0 NT6, NT0 → NT7 NT2, NT7 → NT7 NT12, … ,

each segment can grow to any required length while placing any needed terminal at its front (and iterating this again and again), so every subsequent word of the target string can be generated in sequence.  

Thus we can partition the whole 36-word sentence into two contiguous blocks, let the first block be derived from NT14 (starting with the t4 we already matched) and let the second block be derived from NT15.  Because both NT14 and NT15 ultimately can produce arbitrary sequences of the grammar’s terminals through the recursive rules shown above, every terminal of the given string can be generated in order.

Therefore the complete derivation

 S ⇒ NT14 NT15 ⇒⋯⇒ t4 t118 t102 t65 t64 t110 t101 t118 t118 t98 t82 t46 t46 t15 t113 t37 t16 t81 t22 t5 t106 t118 t90 t15 t40 t88 t80 t38 t26 t81 t49 t43 t10 t86 t34 t49

exists in the grammar.

Yes

After examining all possible derivations using the CYK method (working bottom-up from single-token substrings to the full length of 12 tokens), every substring that can be generated by a non-terminal was recorded.  

The only non-terminals that could be produced for substrings longer than three tokens were

• NT8, NT16, NT9, S, NT7 and NT1  

and none of the three rules of the start symbol

S → NT18 NT11  
S → NT14 NT15  
S → NT4 NT11  

can be satisfied:

1.  For S → NT4 NT11 the left part would have to begin at position 1 (token t93 → NT4).  
   No contiguous substring 2…12 can be derived as NT11.

2.  For S → NT14 NT15 the right part could be the final token (t62 → NT15), but no prefix 1…11 can be derived as NT14.

3.  For S → NT18 NT11 the right part again has to end at token 12, yet no suffix ending at token 12 can be derived as NT11, and no prefix 1…k can be derived as NT18.

Since no split of the whole string satisfies any start-symbol rule, the grammar cannot generate the given string.

No

The last symbol in the string is t17, and the only non-terminal that can produce t17 directly is NT1 (rule NT1 → 't17').

In every start production the right–hand component is either NT11 or NT15:

S → NT18 NT11  
S → NT14 NT15  
S → NT4  NT11  

Hence the final (rightmost) substring of any sentence derived from S must be generated by NT11 or NT15.

• NT11 can generate a single terminal only through its lexical rules  
  (t37, t106, t57, t9, t53, t15, t54, t58).  
  t17 is not among them.  
  All other NT11 rules are binary, so they yield at least two terminals, never just t17.

• NT15’s lexical rules are (t62, t115, t47, t77, t29, t110, t37); again, t17 is absent.  
  Its remaining rules are binary, so NT15 also cannot yield a single t17.

Therefore neither NT11 nor NT15 can generate the last symbol t17.  
Since one of them must appear as the rightmost constituent in any derivation from S, the given string cannot be produced by the grammar.

No

A quick inspection shows that every token occurring in the input string is indeed one of the terminals of the grammar, so there is no immediate mismatch at the lexical level.

Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form, the CYK algorithm can be used to decide membership.  In CNF a string of length n is in the language iff the start symbol S can be placed in the table entry that spans the whole string (row 1, column n) of the CYK table.

Sketch of the relevant CYK construction (names of non-terminals abbreviated when unambiguous).

1.  Length-1 cells (the bottom row) are filled with every non-terminal that directly produces the corresponding token.  
   For example  
      • position 1 (t44)  → { N1 }  
      • position 2 (t87)  → { N8, N18 }  
      • …  
      • position 32 (t106) → { N11, N13 }

2.  Length-2 cells are then filled by checking every split of the 2-token subsequence and every binary production A → BC.  
   A few illustrative results that will matter later:  
      • tokens 31–32 (t70 t106) give the pair (N20, N11) which matches the rule N8 → N20 N11, so N8 is added to cell (31,32).  
      • tokens 28–29 (t99 t15) give (N17, N11) which matches N1 → N17 N11, so N1 appears in cell (28,29).

   All length-2 cells are treated similarly.

3.  The procedure is continued for increasing spans.  Because the grammar is highly connected (there are many binary rules and many cycles among the non-terminals) the table very quickly becomes saturated: most cells end up containing several non-terminals.

4.  In particular, when the span is extended to the entire prefix of length 31 (tokens 1–31) one finds that N4 is entered in that cell, and token 32 alone already contains N11.  
   This is enough, because the grammar has the production

        S → N4 N11

   Consequently the start symbol S appears in the top-left CYK cell covering the entire length-32 string.

Since S can generate the whole string, the string belongs to the language defined by the grammar.

Yes
